Task: Why is Option with if let Some seemingly interfering with interior mutability?

 <p>The following code runs.</p>
<pre><code>use std::{cell::RefCell, rc::Rc};

struct Parent {
    test: bool,
    value: i32,
}

fn main() {
    let parent = Rc::new(RefCell::new(Parent { test: true, value: 42 }));

    if parent.borrow().test {
        parent.borrow_mut().value += 1;
    }
}
</code></pre>
<p>The following code panics with <code>RefCell already borrowed</code>. The only difference is that <code>test</code> is optional.</p>
<pre><code>use std::{cell::RefCell, rc::Rc};

struct Parent {
    test: Option&lt;bool&gt;,
    value: i32,
}

fn main() {
    let parent = Rc::new(RefCell::new(Parent { test: Some(true), value: 42 }));

    if let Some(test) = parent.borrow().test {
        parent.borrow_mut().value += 1;
    }
}
</code></pre>
<p><strong>Why the different behavior?</strong></p>
<p>In the first case, I presume that the borrow is returned after the guard has evaluated, before the body has run. In the second case, this is probably not happening but it should still be possible, I think. It seems like turning <code>test</code> into an <code>Option</code> breaks everything.</p>


