Task: Callbacks in no_std, no_alloc Rust

 <p>Platform: rp2040 (2x Cortex-M0+)</p>
<p>Language: Rust 2024 (no_std, no_alloc)</p>
<p>I'm writing a IRQ handler for DMA. DMA has 12 channels but only 2 IRQs(second IRQ can be ignored for the purpose of this question). When a DMA Channel needs attention the IRQ is triggered and The handler checks a register to see what Channel(s) are finished and acknowledges them. This is where I come to a problem I'd like to have a way to register custom per channel irq (sub)handlers. In C I'd do something like this:</p>
<pre><code>static void no_op(void) {
    return;
}

static void (*channel_handlers[12])(void) = { no_op };

void irq_handler(void) {
    uint32_t reg = read_register();
    for (int ch = 0; ch &lt; 12; ch++) {
        if ((reg &amp; (1u &lt;&lt; ch)) != 0U) {
            channel_handlers[ch]();
        }
    }
    write_register(reg); // Acknowledge channels that were processed

}

void register_channel_handler(int channel, void (*handler)(void)) {
    if (handler == NULL) {
        channel_handlers[channel] = no_op;
    } else {
        channel_handlers[channel] = handler;
    }
}
</code></pre>
<p>However I do not know how to implement that in no_std, no_alloc Rust. I've started with storing sub-handlers as <code>Option&lt;fn()&gt;</code>. Then I've tried packing that in <code>Cell</code>/<code>UnsafeCell</code> but I can't make the compiler happy. I've tried reading up on <code>Box</code>, <code>Arc</code> and the like but those are unsuitable.</p>
<p>How to implement this mechanism or something that gives equivalent functionality?</p>


